text: OMG, as if getting coal for Christmas wasn't bad enough!  Now people get death?!  =0 At 1:13, the creepy old lady character they stereotypically throw into these kind of movies for exposition says "Instead, a much darker, ancient spirit" and then at 1:50 says "He is the shadow of Saint Nicholas" as if darkness and shadows are scary, evil, or unnatural.  But there's no need to be afraid of the dark or of our shadow, and they are not a negative or unnatural things.  It's kind of odd how some people feel about darkness.  When talking about certain things, some people equate the dark to being scary, bad, or evil, but I never could understand it.  =/ This is just a philosophical thought, but if darkness has been around ever since the beginning of everything before anything else, is all around us, and there is even inside of us (I imagine it gets pretty dark inside of our bodies.  I don't think we have light bulbs inside of us), and follows us around in the form of our shadow, isn't darkness one of the most natural and non-evil things out there?  =o And night time is actually one of the most peaceful times for most people.  It's when we rewind, recharge, and heal.  Can't people just say what they mean? Could have easily said "evil" there, you know. l=/ And I've heard some things about this Krampus.  I've heard he punishes the bad.  So does that, in a way, make him good?  He's like a supernatural Punisher or something.  l=D

text: When I saw the "Krampus" title was not expecting to see so many recognizable actors in this movie.  I already know the tales of Krampus so I was expecting the typical b-movie cast.  Not that Toni Collette, Adam Scott, and David Koechner are exactly A-list celebrities, but they are known to star in bigger movies, typically comedies.  This film is listed as a black-comedy though so maybe there will be some good laughs..... which actually kind of upsets me because I think the Krampus character needs to be a full blown horror flick.  We shall see though.  Definitely will wait to rent this though on demand.  Can't see myself blowing $20+ to go see it in theaters when you include nachos and a drink.

text: The Krampus is an very old AUSTRIAN legend.  If you come to Austria in the winter you will find the Krampus' everywhere. But I don't mean just pictures or something like that, no.. There are maaaany events where people dress up as a Krampus with a coat of a goat, a carved mask of wood and stilts to scare other people. Everybody knows that they aren't real, that they are just normal people, but everybody is scared because they look so scary. (If you didn't understand what I mean, just tipe in "Krampuslauf" on YouTube!)  If you want to experience a horror movie live, then just come to Austria ;-)

text: This is far closer to the origins of Santa Claus than St Nicholas - He was actually based on Odin (Woden) the chief God of Northern Europe, who visited houses in the disguise of a Terrible Goat who walked on 2 cloven hooves at Yule time (12 days at the Winter solstice) searching for who had been Bad (naughty) or Good (nice) The Bad didn't make it through the winter.

text: This wasn't bad at all. Not scary, but worth watching for bad-ass Aunt Dorothy.   They tried to show real snow, which can be up to your thighs,  and believe me, running is out of the question. Walking is a trick. But at least it's not the lame and unreal Hollywood snow, which is minor at best, and not even cold, much less dangerous. I that kind of snow/cold, you're not going anywhere without clothes and a hat on. Once it's below 0, you'll notice the lack of clothes right away and it hurts to breathe.   The breath-seeing is bad CGI, though. See "Titanic" for the same effect, but done realistically.   I liked it, and out of 10 movies or more I get from the library, maybe one makes it past 5 minutes. TV shows, dramas, sitcoms, and rom-coms and particularly horror movies don't age well.   Could've sworn this was a horror movie in the 80's...  Btw, how does a young kid in the 'burbs know how to drive anything?? If so, you'd think he'd know about flooding carbs, right, assuming he somehow learned in the country where they still have lots of old vehicles...(if you smell gas, you have to flood it all the way out by putting the gas pedal on the floor)   PS, if you have snow to your thighs, it's extremely unlikely you are hearing any sirens, because no one's going anywhere...I've seen snow like that in a major city.   "It's only a block. We can walk!" Oh, yeah? They've never seen it as cold as they're talking about. You're not likely walking anywhere.
